Ten-hour monitoring of patient-occupied isolation rooms took place on three separate sampling days from 08:00 to 18:00 h. The first case study (Figure 1
a) involved a 71-year-old male patient, who had undergone partial pancreatectomy for cancer and multi-organ failure, who occupied the room for 8 days prior to commencement of air monitoring. Results (Table I
) demonstrate a high degree of variability over the 10-h period, with a mean airborne bacterial load of 64.3 [standard deviation (SD) 31.8 cfu/m3], a minimum of 12 cfu/m3 and a maximum of 166 cfu/m3. This maximum (Observation 16 at 11:45 h) was statistically classified as ‘out of control’, and coincided with collection after fresh bed sheets were shaken in preparation of a bed change.
